- "bloomed into their latest versions" refers to the latest version release date being on or after January 1, 2021;
- "dawn of 2021" refers to the start of the year 2021;
- "last blossomed" refers to the latest release date of the software product;
- "most recent updates to their underlying databases" refers to the latest update date of the associated databases.

- "Garden of code changes" refers to the changelog entries in the database;
- "Contributors" refers to the users who have made changes;
- "Hands have shaped the most entries" refers to the users with the highest number of changelog entries.

- "Product versions with at least one change" refers to versions that have been modified or updated at least once;
- "Names and roles of the users involved" include the full names and roles of the users who made the changes;
- "Release dates in descending order" means the most recent releases are listed first;
- "Changelog count in descending order" means versions with more changes are listed first.

- 'major releases' refers to versions where `major_release` is 1;
- 'added new features' refers to changes where `change_type_category` is 'feature';
- 'since the dawn of the new year in 2021' refers to changes made on or after January 1, 2021.

- A "version" refers to a specific release or iteration of a software product;
- "Most recent changes" are determined by the latest `change_date` in the `changelogs` table;
- The `author` in the `changelogs` table corresponds to the `user_id` in the `users` table, which holds the `user_name`.

- Major releases are significant updates to a software product, often denoted by a major version number change;
- Changelog entries document the changes made in each version of the software;
- Users can have different roles such as developer, QA engineer, or project manager.

